relative or at some other place;

(ii)  that  the  probationer  shall  attend  an  educational 
institution  to  be  recommended  by  the  probation 
officer;

(a)  the  Court  shall  forthwith  give  sufficient  copies  of  the 
amending  or  discharging  order  to  the  probation  officer; 
and

(c)  remove by force any obstruction to entry, search, seizure, 
detention or removal as he is empowered to effect under 
subsection (2);

(a)  refuses the Protector or Social Welfare Officer access to 
any  premises,  or  fails  to  submit  to  a  search  by  a  person 
authorized to search him under this Act;

(c)  fails  to  comply  with  any  lawful  demand,  order  or 
requirement of a Protector, Assistant  Protector or Social 
Welfare Officer in the execution of his duty under this Act;

(d)  omits, refuses or neglects to give to a Protector or Social 
Welfare Officer any information which may be reasonably 
required of him and which he is empowered to give;

(a)  delivering the document to that person or by delivering the 
document  at  the  last  known  place  of  residence  of  that 
person to an adult member of his family;

(a)  to  prescribe  the  conduct,  management,  discipline  and 
control  of  approved  schools,  Henry  Gurney  Schools, 
probation hostels, places of detention or centres;

to  prescribe  the  selection  and  qualifications  of  fit  and 
proper  persons  with  whom  a  child  in  need  of  care  and 
protection may be placed;

to  prescribe  the  composition,  duties,  functions  and 
procedures  of  conducting  the  business  of  Boards  of 
Visitors;

(n)  to prescribe the particulars, photographs or other means of 
identification to be furnished in relation to a child in need 
of protection;

(p)  to prescribe the records to be kept in respect of every child 
in need of protection and the manner in which the records 
shall be kept;

(s)  to  prescribe  the  form  of  notices,  orders,  warrants, 
summonses and bonds under this Act and the manner of 
service thereof;

“repealed Acts” means the Juvenile Courts Act 1947 [Act  90], the 
Women  and  Girls  Protection  Act  1973  [Act  106]  and  the  Child 
